Expansion work done $(k J)=$ ?<div></div>
Condition: Constant pressure<div></div>
Work done during expansion at constant pressure can be calculated using the formula:<div></div>$$
W=-P \Delta V
$$<div></div>


Using the ideal gas law, $P V=n R T$<div></div>
so, $P \Delta V=\Delta n R T$<div></div>

$$
\therefore W=-\Delta n R T
$$

$\Delta n$ - change in number of moles of gas<div></div>
$\Delta n$ can be determined by analysing the electrolysis reaction of water:
The reaction occuring is<div></div>$$
2 \mathrm{H}_2 \mathrm{O}(\mathrm{l}) \longrightarrow 2 \mathrm{H}_2(\mathrm{~g})+\mathrm{O}_2(\mathrm{~g})
$$<div></div>$$
\text { Moles of } \mathrm{H}_2 \mathrm{O} \text { (Water) }=\frac{\text { mass given }}{\text { molar mass }} \quad {\mathrm{H}_2 \mathrm{O} \text { molar }}{\text { mass }=18 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}
$$<div></div>$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\frac{1449}{1891 \mathrm{~mol}} \\
& =8 \mathrm{~mol}
\end{aligned}
$$<div></div>From the balanced equation, 2 moles of $H_2 0$ produce 2 moles of $\mathrm{H}_2$ and 1 mole of $0_2$. So, 8 moles of $\mathrm{H}_2 \mathrm{O}$ will produce 8 moles of $\mathrm{H}_2$ and 4 moles of $O_2$.<div></div>The total moles of gas produced $=$ moles of $\mathrm{H}_2+$ moles of $\mathrm{O}_2$<div></div>$$
\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,=8 \mathrm{~mol}+4 \mathrm{~mol}=12 \mathrm{~mol}
$$<div></div>$$
\Delta n=\text { moles of gaseous products - moles of gaseous reactants }
$$<div></div>$$
\begin{aligned}
